  <main>
    <section>
      <h2>Purpose</h2>
      <p>
        This project aims to <strong>adapt and co-design pulmonary rehabilitation (PR) tools</strong> for people with
        <strong>Alpha-1 Antitrypsin Deficiency (AATD)</strong>. We focus on making PR more <strong>personalised,
        practical, and follow-up friendly</strong> by embedding a <em>Treatable Traits (TT)</em> approach and using
        <em>Experience-Based Co-Design (EBCD)</em> with patients and clinicians.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Why AATD-Tailored PR?</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Symptoms and needs vary (e.g., breathlessness variability, anxiety, oxygen setup, deconditioning).</li>
        <li>Generic PR pathways can miss AATD-specific traits and the need for structured follow-up.</li>
        <li>Patients value clear, portable tools (targets, pacing, “good/bad day” cues, flare plans) they can use across settings.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What This Hub Includes</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Trait→Plan checklist (A4)</strong> — maps traits to actions for clinicians.</li>
        <li><strong>Exercise Passport (A6)</strong> — patient booklet with targets, RPE guidance, and simple progression rules.</li>
        <li><strong>Stay-Active Kit</strong> — quick-use cards (two-week ramp, pacing & breathing cues, habit tracker, relapse/flare plan).</li>
        <li><strong>Workshop materials</strong> — agendas, case study, and usability prompts.</li>
        <li><strong>Outputs</strong> — visual abstract and summary reports as the work progresses.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Start here: <a href="../prototypes/index.html">Prototypes</a> · <a href="../sessions/session1-agenda.html">Workshop 1</a> · <a href="how-to-use.html">Using this Hub</a></p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Who’s Involved</h2>
      <p>People with AATD, caregivers, PR clinicians, and researchers at the University of Birmingham.</p>
      <p>The hub builds on a multi-method programme (systematic review, cohort analysis, qualitative study, and Delphi consensus). See <a href="../outputs/index.html">Outputs</a>.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Data & Acknowledgements</h2>
      <p>
        Co-design sessions focus on usability and acceptability. Materials are for research and service-improvement use.
        Please do not redistribute without permission. For questions or access issues, email
        <a href="mailto:f.a.alwadani@bham.ac.uk">f.a.alwadani@bham.ac.uk</a>.
      </p>
    </section>
